article.headline: Minnesota 63, South Carolina 53
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Minnesota's big two were at it again
Saturday, this time showing the rest of the country why the Golden
Gophers have become a national power.

Lindsay Whalen scored 24 points and reached a career milestone,
while teammate Janel McCarville added 18 points and clutch defense
as No. 6 Minnesota knocked off South Carolina 63-53.

Minnesota's team defense was the biggest star in the first
nationally televised regular-season game in school history. The
Gophers held the Gamecocks to 27 points below their season average,
and after South Carolina had cut the Minnesota lead to six points
with 2:12 to play, the Gophers (12-0) came up with five straight
defensive stops to pull away.

"I told the team we needed four stops on defense at the end of
the game, and I think we got five," Gophers coach Pam Borton said.
"That's what wins games and wins championships."

The Gopher defense was keyed by the play of McCarville, who had
a game-high four blocked shots, six steals and nine rebounds. The
junior center missed a week of practice with the flu but played 36
minutes, which was crucial against South Carolina's bigger lineup.

"Janel anticipates extremely well defensively," Borton said.
"She's the best help defender on the team. She's very aggressive
and reads well, so she knows when she can help."

Meanwhile, Whalen became the third player in school history to
score 2,000 points when she converted a twisting layup and the
ensuing free throw on a three-point play with 8:27 left in the
game. The senior guard has 2,004 career points and trails Carol Ann
Shudlick by 93 points for Minnesota's all-time lead.

Whalen also became the fifth player in NCAA history to amass
2,000 points and 500 assists in her career.

"Obviously it's a nice accomplishment to do something only four
other people have done, but we've got a lot to accomplish this year
as a team, so you can't get too caught up with it," Whalen said.

Iva Sliskovic led the Gamecocks (8-4) with 15 points, but the
6-foot-5 freshman also committed 10 turnovers. Free throws were a
key factor in the outcome -- South Carolina was a mere 3-for-8 from
the line, while Minnesota made 14 of 20 free throws, including 13
of 16 in the second half. Whalen and McCarville went 6-for-6 in the
final minute as Minnesota pulled away.

South Carolina got five points from Lauren Simms during a 7-0
run midway through the first half to take a 20-16 lead.

But the Gophers responded with a 16-2 spurt, using precision
inside passing and their transition game to take a 36-26 lead at
the half. Whalen got the run started with a no-look pass to Shannon
Bolden for a layup, and added a three-pointer, steal and fast-break
basket in a 20-second span. Whalen then capped the half with an
acrobatic drive to the hoop for a buzzer-beating layup in traffic.

The Gamecocks converted Minnesota turnovers into easy layups on
three consecutive possessions early in the second half, cutting the
Gophers lead to 40-32. But Whalen again came to the rescue, hitting
a pull-up jumper in the lane, then breaking down the defense and
setting up Bolden for another layup to secure the Gophers' lead.

McCarville made the defensive play of the game with 1:30 to play
and the Gophers leading by just six. She swatted the ball out of
Sliskovic's hands, then flopped to the floor, corralled the loose
ball and called a timeout to keep possession.

Minnesota scored the next six points to seal the victory.
